<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the real interest rate when expected inflation increases but nominal interest rates don't change?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Real interest rate increases</option>
            <option letter="b">Real interest rate decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">Real interest rate stays the same</option>
            <option letter="d">Real interest rate becomes negative</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When expected inflation increases but nominal interest rates remain constant, the real interest rate decreases because real interest rate equals nominal interest rate minus expected inflation rate.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in the velocity of money affect the price level, assuming constant money supply and real GDP?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Price level decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Price level increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Price level stays constant</option>
            <option letter="d">Effect cannot be determined</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>With constant money supply and real GDP, an increase in velocity means each dollar is being spent more frequently, leading to a higher price level according to the quantity theory of money.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What distinguishes automatic stabilizers from discretionary fiscal policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Automatic stabilizers require congressional approval</option>
            <option letter="b">Automatic stabilizers work without policy action</option>
            <option letter="c">Automatic stabilizers only work during expansions</option>
            <option letter="d">Automatic stabilizers only affect government spending</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Automatic stabilizers work without requiring specific policy actions, automatically helping to stabilize the economy through mechanisms like progressive taxes and unemployment benefits.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in capital mobility affect the effectiveness of monetary policy in a fixed exchange rate system?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases monetary policy effectiveness</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases monetary policy effectiveness</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on monetary policy</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects fiscal policy</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Increased capital mobility reduces monetary policy effectiveness under fixed exchange rates because the central bank must focus on maintaining the exchange rate rather than managing domestic economic conditions.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
